          "type": "tool_use",
          "name": "Write",
          "input": {
            "content": "## Summary\n\nThe keystone. The API thread only validates the request, stores the message, creates the run, enqueues it, and returns the run id. A **worker** resolves config, runs the agent loop, invokes tools, and appends to an **append-only run-event store**.\n\n## Context\n\nSPEC.md §9.1–§9.5. Depends on the config resolver (#46) and the queue (#47). This is the boundary that makes runs durable and refresh-safe.\n\n## Design\n\nTables:\n\n- `runs(id, chat_id, message_id, user_id, status, worker_id, started_at, completed_at, error_json)`\n- `run_events(run_id, sequence, event_type, payload_json, created_at)` — append-only, **monotonic `sequence` per run**\n\nFlow (SPEC §9.5):\n\n1. **API:** store message + `run.created` → enqueue (pg-boss) → return `run_id`. No agent work.\n2. **Worker:** `run.started` → resolve + snapshot config (#46) → retrieval/model/tool loop → emit events → `run.completed`.\n\nStatuses per SPEC §9.3; event types per §9.4. Idempotency keys, cancellation, run timeout, worker heartbeat. LangGraph drives the agent loop inside the worker (wired in #50); the event store — not LangGraph memory — is the durable source of truth.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] API performs only validate / store / enqueue / return (SPEC §9.5)\n- [ ] worker consumes from pg-boss and appends ordered `run_events`\n- [ ] idempotent (retry-safe), cancellable, with heartbeat + timeout\n- [ ] run status transitions match SPEC §9.3\n\n## Requirements\n\n- #46 — config resolver + run snapshot\n- #47 — pg-boss queue + scheduler\n",
